description: 1969 Mach one Q-Code Super Cobra Jet 4 speed drag-pak 3.91 axle. Family history since 1979.

This 1969 Mustang Mach one is 1 or 361 Q-Code cars produced. The car was built may 1st 1969. According to the deluxe Marti report only a mere six came with the Super Cobra Jet engine, of which only 3 were produced with 3.91 traction-lok axles. This rare example was shipped to a Ford dealer in Geneva NY, the car was ordered with the following features; 428 SCJ engine, 4 speed close ratio transmission, traction-lok differential F-70x14” traction tires with raised white letters, power front disc brakes, AM radio and complete tinted glass. Currently the car is in our showroom and looking at the cars exterior appearance we noticed the car has only had single repaint and the body, sheet metal, floors and storage boxes are extremely solid straight body panels with no waves in the cars exterior body. Original chrome bumpers, brightwork, original tinted glass including the windshield, spoilers, Slats, 15” American racing torque thrust wheels mounted on cooper cobra raised white letter radials. Only a few touch ups in the cars paint noticed, the rear quarters, doors, fenders hood and trunk lid are super nice. This Q-Code has always been stored inside, no winters and it shows by looking at the cars underside.

The cars deluxe interior is completely original. Minimal wear on the interior. Dash pad is excellent; seats are showing their age but very presentable. Center console has a Stewart Warner oil pressure gauge drilled in the console plate. Gorgeous original door panels, instrument cluster is excellent, all the gauges work including the factory tach. The headliner, sail panels are in excellent shape and they appear to be original as well as a complete set of original seat belts. Hurst factory shifter Tee Handle shifter knob, Rim Blow steering wheels, remote driver side mirror and a clock which is inoperable.

Looking under the hood has #’s matching 428 super cobra jet engine, you’ll notice the original air cleaner element is missing. The car is mostly original under the hood, factory Buck Tag solid original inner fender aprons, original radiator support with the original oil cooler, original single point distributor, heads, intake, exhaust manifolds with 2 ½ exhaust with flow master mufflers. The number on the back of the block is 9D300 which is April 30, 1969 which is just 21 days before it was built on May 21, 1969. There is no VIN # on the back of the bloc, however it appears, based on our research, this is the original engine but we have no supporting documents to prove it.  The 3.91 gears are in a box in the trunk. Currently the car has 3.50 axle ratio makes it more user friendly for the street. We have searched out the correct wheels and tires, air cleaner element and exhaust system parts which would make the car more correct. Cost for the parts are about $3500.

This ultra-rare Q-Code is considered an excellent driver quality car that has great bones! Comes with owner history dating back to 1979. 88,000 miles are actual, the car performs well and shifts smooth. A pure muscle machine, low production Super Cobra Jet drag-pak car!
Comes with a deluxe Marti report and a lot of interesting history!
Must see to really appreciate!

description: The Boss 429 Mustang is a high-performance Ford Mustang variant that was offered by Ford in 1969 and 1970. The Boss 429 (also known as the "Boss 9" by enthusiasts) is arguably one of the rarest and most valued muscle cars to date. In total there were 1358 original Boss 429s made. The origin of the Boss 429 came about as a result of NASCAR. Ford was seeking to develop a Hemi engine that could compete with the famed 426 Hemi from Chrysler in NASCAR's Sprint Cup Series (then known as "Grand National Division"). NASCAR's homologation rules required that at least 500 cars be fitted with this motor and sold to the general public. After much consideration, it was decided by Ford that the Mustang would be the car that would house this new engine.

GR Auto Gallery is pleased to present this 1969 Ford Mustang Boss 429 for your consideration. According to the Deluxe Marti Report, this Pony was first delivered to Front Royal Motors, INC., of Front Royal Virginia. It was produced in April of 1969, built in Dearborn, Michigan, it was spec'd in Royal Maroon with Black Clarion Knit Vinyl Hi-Back Seats. In addition to the 429ci high output v8 engine, four-speed manual transmission, and traction-lok differential, it was equipped with the visibility group. Some key features of this Pony include; KK no. 1692, matching numbers 429ci engine and drivetrain, just over 36,000 original miles, engine compartment is original and unpainted, one full repaint in the original Royal Maroon, rear trunk area is original, unpainted, and included original spare tire and inflation bottle, period correct polyglass tires, Autolite battery and 1969 date-coded windshield, Concours restoration that was completed in 2012, all original body, all original interior, included partial factory build sheet, original dealer invoice, original Kar Kraft invoice, deluxe Marti report, and this vehicle was even owned by Jeremy Feller of the Boss 429 data base. According to the owner, this vehicle starts easily and runs strong and the transmission shifts smoothly through all gears. Please contact us for more information on this 1969 Ford Mustang Boss 429.
To see over 80 photos of this car, including under carriage please visit our website www.grautogallery.com

description: 1969 Shelby GT350 Convertible For Sale - Rare Acapulco Blue, 4 Speed, Rotisserie Restored LMC is very proud to offer for sale this 1969 Shelby GT350 Convertible. The next generation Shelby Mustang GTs for 1969 saw the GT350 equipped with a 351 cubic-inch V8 and the GT500 with Ford’s mega 428 block power plant.  Upscale, professional and well off, the buyers Shelby and Ford targeted wanted performance at their disposal but, also demanded their performance cars be comfortable and reliable daily drivers. The 1969 model year received an extensive face lift with the body increasing in length by 4 inches. The new exterior look for 1969 was long and low with racy styling having looks that seems to dare anything on the road to try and challenge it. These Shelby’s were known for racing car handling in the day with lots of power to the asphalt and the suspension and brakes to take a corner at speed and ride right through the curve. In 1969, there were only 194 GT350 Convertibles that rolled off the assembly line compared to the 335 GT500 Convertibles. This makes the GT350 much rarer than the GT500 in the opinion of many Shelby fans. Turn the chrome button hood locks and lift the functional vented hood and underneath is the Numbers Matching M-Code 351 power plant that defined this model year of Shelby Mustangs. This Shelby has the rare and very desirable factory ordered 4-Speed Wide Ratio Manual Transmission sporting the wood knob shifter mounted in its console. This is linked up to the 3.25 Traction-Lok Axle. Goodyear Polyglas raised letter tires mounted on Shelby five spoke chrome wheels drives this machine. Power exits through two rectangular ports located in the center under the license plate out the back. Power front disc, rear drum brakes and power steering were mandatory options. This GT350 is 1 of only 42 to leave the factory in Acapulco Blue and complimented nicely by its black interior and Black Power Soft Top. There are dual body tone racing mirrors with the Driver Remote Mirror. The Shelby’s interior of Black Clarion Knit Vinyl has excellent seat surfaces and overall great condition ready to be fully enjoyed by the next Shelby enthusiast. The paint is in a show quality condition and far better than it ever left the factory back in 1969. Other conveniences of the day include an AM Radio, Tach, Clock, Driver-Remote Chrome Mirror as well as an Oil/Amp gauges mounted under the dash in front of the shifter. This 1969 Shelby GT350 Convertible is a rare, unique, highly sought after and very desirable with only 42 factory built in this color. Being rotisserie restored and fully documented, this Shelby GT350 would be a statement piece in any collection. Additional Details: 1969 FORD MUSTANG SHELBY GT350 -

description: This 1969 Ford Mustang Mach 1 fastback has every trick you could want wrapped in standout package. Beneath the bold blue lies serious firepower in the form of the original 351 V8 rebuilt and supercharged to 650hp.  Plus, upgrades to the four-speed, suspension, and even the interior are all part of a full restoration that fortifies this total performance Ford.

This one is all about getting that genuine Mach 1 Mustang feeling while also being distinctly upgraded. The factory-correct blacked-out hood mixes with the proper gold Mach 1 stripes on the side and rear to give this both an aggressive and upper-class appearance.  Plus, the large hood scoop and rear wing are always great performance signposts.  You see all these features so clearly because this is a long term labor of love that took this coupe down to the bare metal.  All imperfections were addressed and the panels were stitch welded for greater strength.  Only after the body was made its best was paint allowed back on the sheetmetal.  The blue has all the right tones to be a 1969-correct Acapulco Blue, but in this case, the modern clearcoat really gives it a greater depth like a deep blue ocean.  But even as this coupe has all the right pieces for its iconic year â€“ from the mirror-like chrome bumpers to proper badging â€“ there is also a nice hint at the upgrades within.  The large 18-inch Halibrand-style wheels on the lowered suspension is a clear signal to true Mustang fans to really watch out for this one.

There is no better muscle car interior than black, but this one does it better with added aggression and comfort. For starters, Ford was going for a more luxurious image with these coupes, and you see it in factory pieces like the center console and all that wood paneling.  But take a closer look, and you'll see some great upgrades.  For example, you could get high back bucket seats with the aggressive red streaks from the factory, but these leather TMI units take Ford's Comfort Weave style and add modern bolstering and cool red stitching.  Even the stereo is a modern Bluetooth unit disguised as a knob-style radio.  You still get the factory three-spoke steering wheel that gives you a commanding view of the full gauge panel, including large tach.  But now you also have a set of auxiliary gauges in the center console to keep you fully informed.  And just in front of that is likely your favorite feature.  After all, the Hurst cue ball shifter is an icon all on its own.

Usually having the original V8 under the hood is the main item people want to talk about, but on this one, there is something even more special. That shiny ProCharger supercharger looks great, and more importantly, gives this 351 V8 a serious upgrade in power. With the ability to create some muscle, the rest of the V8 was fortified to handle the performance.  It was rebuilt to include a .030 bore, Quick Fuel four-barrel carburetor, Edelbrock Victor Jr intake, and Canfield aluminum heads.  The total output was dyno certified at 650hp at the crank.  Making sure the rest of the package could handle the monster motor meant the original four-speed was rebuilt by Dan Williams Top Loader Transmissions.  Plus, the 9-inch rear was rebuilt including a new limited slip differential and a versatile 3.50 ratio.  Plus, the suspension upgrades include thick sway bars front & rear, new urethane bushings, and traction bars.  Stopping is also well in hand with a full Wilwood four-wheel disc brake package and the modern grip of Nitto NT555 tires.

There's so many more features to this amazing build, so you should call for all the details.  But you already know this is the kind of classic build that only comes around once in a lifetime.  How cool is it to drive a supercharged '69 Mach 1? You'll never know unless you call today!

description: The Ford Mustang Boss 302 is an icon among icons, a car from the pinnacle of the muscle car era that does more with less and as a result has become a blue-chip collectable. And for many of us, there's one in the past that got away, and now with prices on these cars skyrocketing, we thought we'd never get to own one of these awesome cars. Well, this 1969 Boss 302 tribute offers a more affordable way to own a legend, one with a few smart upgrades that you'd never find in an original Boss, and a high-dollar rotisserie restoration to boot, making this car the best of both worlds.

Now, we're not going to tell you that this is a real car, because you've already figured that out by the price. It's a very fresh restoration that's built for showing and driving, and if you've experienced a Boss 302 already, then you know that driving is what they do best. Grabber Orange isn't this car's original color, but it's the right color on a Boss, so that's what went on when the car was refinished. In fact, the paint is only six months old and has about 14 miles on it, so it's incredibly fresh and bright and done to a very high standard, completed by one of the most respectable shops in Atlanta. The Boss graphics are expertly applied and the body doesn't show any critical issues that would suggest a checkered past and the blacked out hood and deck lid are painted satin black for effect. Factory rear window louvers, a factory rear spoiler, and the blacked-out tail panel all work well with the bright orange paint and gorgeous chrome bumpers to give this Boss just the right look.

The black interior is especially nice, with new seat covers on the original buckets, correct door panels, and the critical Hurst shifter. The seats look upscale in the Mustang's all-black interior, and you can see why this was such a great place to do the serious business of driving fast. Factory gauges are original, but they work just fine and there are new bulbs inside, so they light up brightly at night. The original AM radio is gone, replaced by an AM/FM/iPod stereo that fits like it was born there. The shifter is a proper Hurst unit, complete with cue ball knob, but you'll note that it now manages five gears, not four, making this Boss a weapon on the street yet comfortable on the highway. The back seat looks almost new, and the neatly finished trunk offers a correct plaid mat that fits rather well.

The 302 cubic inch V8 that is the heart of the Boss looks awesome in the engine bay and even though it's not the real thing, it sure looks convincing.  It's correctly dressed in Ford Blue with a big air cleaner and proper reproduction decals, all of which make the 1969s unique. Upgrades include an Edelbrock intake manifold and Holley 4-barrel carburetor, and there's a Comp Cams bumpstick inside that gives it that famous cackling boss idle. title: 1969 Ford Mustang

description: You stopped to take a look at this 1969 Ford Mustang because you saw the affordable price.  But when you discover the cool ghost flame paint and upgraded V8, you soon realize this is an icon with extra value.

This pony car started out as a L-code hardtop coupe, but it was destined for much more.  The glossy silver is attention-grabbing, but what really draws them in is the front end.  Custom ghost flames in a faint shade of metallic pink make this coupe look like there is some serious aggression below the surface.  And this one even backs up this intimidation in its details like the front air dam, fog lights in the grille, and dark rear spoiler.  Plus, while the bumpers and dual exhaust tips shine nicely, we know your favorite piece of brightwork is the set of those cool American Racing solid wheels.

The forceful attitude continues with an all-black interior.  From the door panels, to the seats, to the dash, to the carpets, everything in this Mustang looks like midnight. This is truly setup for the driver with a factory premium steering wheel that gives you a clear view of the full round gauge panel.  Plus, there's a nice auxiliary gauge trio.  But passengers won't feel like an afterthought thanks to features like cup holders and the upgraded AM/FM/CD stereo for everyone to enjoy.

Under the hood is a cool presentation of diamond plating on the fender walls and plenty of gloss black accessories.  But your favorite part should be the 289 cubic-inch motor.  We believe it was rebuilt around 1,000 miles ago, and this trusty V8 now also has performance upgrades like a Holley four-barrel carburetor and Weiand intake.  They add an extra kick of power to the V8 and help the glasspack-style dual exhaust have an extra deep growl.  But more than just a mean machine, this one was built to be an easy driver.  Features like three-speed automatic transmission, power steering, front disc brakes are great to have when you want a vintage coupe that's easy to drive on a whim.

A cool classic with some nice upgrades is always a fine choice...especially when it's this affordable.  But you're not the only one who can fit this Mustang into the budget.  So don't miss out, hurry up and call today!
title: 1969 Ford Mustang

description: This 1969 Mustang Sportsroof is a base trim model (63A) built in San Jose as an R-code 428 Cobra Jet with Ram Air, C6 automatic and 3.50 axle ratio. As a base car, there is no faux Mach 1 style woodgrain overlay surrounding the very rare factory installed tachometer cluster or distracting the passenger view which gives the interior a contemporary look. Because this is a factory CJ, it has all of the same mechanical upgrades that the CJ Mach 1 received including Competitive suspension (swings, front sway bar, shocks), power front disc brakes and larger rear drums, reinforced shock towers and reinforced export braces, 9-inch rear axle, heavy duty cooling, fast ratio 16:1 steering (power assisted with PS fluid cooler in this car), and 14x6 styled steel wheels with F70x14 wide oval belted tires. The base trim model has a monotone exterior, deleting the blackout hood treatment, side/rear stripes and base trim model has a monotone exterior, deleting the blackout hood treatment, side/rear stripes, and moldings of a Mach 1 but still has its original shaker hood scoop topping the Cobra Jet.

Documentation is very important and with this 1969 Mustang, the original build sheet and Deluxe Marti report and a very large amount of receipts and records are contained in a documents book. That doc book also contains additional items authenticating originality; pictures that show casting dates and matching assembly plant build tags on transmission and axle to the build sheet. Marti report is included that tells us as one of the 465 Cobra Jet non-Mach 1’s, when options are added, it becomes 1 of 1, as originally built. This 1969 Was just freshened with a full repaint, although not in the original Black Jade with Ivy Gold interior, the Red base coat clear coat exterior is a very close match to contemporary Race Red with Black Standard Trim Interior which was also freshened with new carpet and complete underlayment. As well, the trunk has been cleaned and resprayed and includes a correct spare wheel/tire. To Keep this 47-year-old car running and enjoyable to drive, all maintenance and wear items have been addressed. Cooling, brakes, fuel, power steering, ignition, suspension, lighting, and radio have all received a rebuilt and or upgrade. To modernize the driving experience, the front suspension has been upgraded to a stealthy Bilstein coilover system designed and built by a dedicated classic Mustang-only suspension shop that proves his systems on the track and street. This Pony has the right stance, nose down with classic chip spoiler, 17” 5-spoke wheels and 235/45 front and 255/45 rear tires filling the big wheel arches. It stands out in a crowd, is comfortable to drive, has original details, original cobra jet power, and benefits from functional upgrades. This is a Pony you do not want to miss, please call or email us today for more information.
